# Unit Testing with Vitest

This project uses [Vitest](https://vitest.dev/) and [React Testing Library](https://testing-library.com/docs/react-testing-library/intro/) for unit testing.

## Setup

Dependencies (already installed as dev dependencies):
- `vitest`
- `@vitejs/plugin-react`
- `jsdom`
- `@testing-library/react`
- `@testing-library/dom`
- `vite-tsconfig-paths`

Config lives at `vitest.config.mts` in the project root:

```ts
import { defineConfig } from 'vitest/config'
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react'
import tsconfigPaths from 'vite-tsconfig-paths'

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [tsconfigPaths(), react()],
  test: {
    environment: 'jsdom',
  },
})
```

Run tests with:
```bash
pnpm test
```

## Where to Put Tests

- Colocate test files inside `app/` next to the component
- Test files must end in `.test.tsx` or `.test.ts`

## Writing Tests

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — synchronous Client or Server Component
import { expect, test } from 'vitest'
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react'
import MyComponent from '../app/some/path/MyComponent'

test('renders heading', () => {
  render(<MyComponent />)
  expect(screen.getByRole('heading', { level: 1, name: 'Title' })).toBeDefined()
})
```

## Limitations

> `async` Server Components are **not supported** by Vitest. Write unit tests only for synchronous Server Components and Client Components. Use E2E tests (e.g. Playwright) for `async` Server Components.

## Rules

- Use `vitest` and `@testing-library/react` — never Jest or Enzyme
- Test files must use `.test.tsx` / `.test.ts` extensions
- Do not test `async` Server Components with Vitest — use E2E tests instead
- Keep tests focused: one component or function per test file
- Use `screen` queries from React Testing Library — never query the DOM directly
